1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 c5 3. e3 Nc6 { [%cal Gf1b5] } 4. Be2 (4. Bb5 { The more principled approach. Bb5 prevents black from taking the center with e5. }) 4... e5 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 e4 7. c4 { [%cal Gg8f6,Gf8b4] } 7... dxc4? (7... Nf6 8. cxd5 Nxd5 { This would have been just a better version of what happened structurally later in the game. }) 8. Bxc4 Nf6 9. Ne2 Bd6 10. Ng3 O-O 11. O-O a6 12. Na3 b5 (12... Ng4!! { Initiating a computer-esque attack on the kingside with Nxh2, Qh4, and e3 allowing most of black's pieces to sweep into the game. } 13. h3 (13. Be2 Nxh2 14. Kxh2 Qh4+ 15. Kg1 e3 16. f4 Qxg3 17. Rf3 Qg6 18. Rxe3 (18. Nc4 Bg4 19. Rxe3 Bxe2 20. Rxe2 Bxf4)) 13... Nxf2) 13. Be2 { [%cal Gf8e8] } 13... Bxg3 (13... Re8 14. d5 Nb4 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 { I wanted to play Re8 but was worried about this position being worse for black because the e4 pawn was overextended. But giving up the bishop just to provide a secure square on e4 was not the correct choice. }) 14. hxg3 Nd5 15. Nc2 Qg5 16. Bc1! { Preventing any e3 ideas for black with tempo. The bishop was blocked in by the d4 pawn when on b2, so this "undeveloping move" is actually an improvement for white. } 16... Qf6 17. Be3 Nc3 { I valued the light squared bishop more than the dark squared bishop here because of black's pawn structure. However, taking the dark squared bishop leads to a damaged kingside structure unless white wants to drop d4. } 18. Qd2 Nxe2+ 19. Qxe2 Be6 20. Rad1 Rfd8 21. f3? exf3 22. Qxf3 Qxf3 23. gxf3 { Forced. Otherwise Bg4 wins the exchange. } 23... a5 24. Bf4 a4 25. Bc7 Rd7 (25... axb3 26. Bxd8 bxc2 27. Rc1 Rxd8 28. Rxc2 Nxd4) 26. d5 Rxd5 27. Rxd5 Bxd5 28. Ne3 axb3! { The bishop is immune to capture because black's pawn will queen (or white will have to later give up a piece to stop it). } 29. axb3 (29. Nxd5 bxa2 30. Ra1 b4 31. Be5 Ra5 32. Bb2 Rxd5 33. Rxa2 Ra5 34. Ra1 Rxa1+ 35. Bxa1) 29... Bxb3 30. Rb1 Bc4 31. Nxc4 bxc4 32. Rb6 Na5?? (32... Nd4 33. Rb4 Rc8 34. Kf2 Ne6 35. Rb8 Rxb8 36. Bxb8 h5) 33. Rb5?? (33. Rb4! Nb3 34. Rxc4 Nd2 35. Rc3 { The saving move Rb4 leads to black only being up a single pawn. This should be a drawn endgame with proper play. }) 33... Nb3 34. Kf2 Rc8 35. Ke3 f6 36. Rb8 Rxb8 37. Bxb8 Kf7 38. Ke4 Ke6 39. Ba7 g6 40. g4 f5+ 41. Ke3 fxg4 42. fxg4 h5 43. gxh5 gxh5 44. Kf4 Kd5 45. Bb8 Kd4?? (45... c3 46. Kf5 c2 47. Bf4 Nd4+ 48. Kg6 Ne6 49. Bc1 h4) 46. Be5+ Kd3 47. Kg5?? (47. Bb2! Kc2 48. Bh8 Kd3 49. Bb2 { And black can't stop Bb2 or Bh8. If c3 ever, Bxc3 leads to a draw. }) 47... Nd4 48. Kxh5 c3 49. Bf4 c2 50. Bc1 Nb3 51. Bb2 Na5 52. Kg4 Kd2 53. Kf3 Nc4! { The only move that stops white's Bishop from staying on the diagonal. Black pushes the pawn through next. } 54. Bc1+ Kxc1 55. Ke2 Kb1 56. Kd3 c1=Q *


