1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. Bd3 c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. Ndf3 cxd4 8. cxd4 f6 9. exf6 Nxf6 10. Ne2 Bd6 { The mainline of the French Tarrasch. } 11. O-O O-O 12. Re1 e5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Ng3 Qc7 (15... Ng4!? { A very interesting move to kickstart a kingside attack of sort. Both f3 and h3 fail in this position. } 16. f3?? (16. h3?? Bxg3 17. fxg3) (16. Bc2 Rxf2 (16... Qh4 17. h3 Bxg3 18. fxg3 Qxg3 19. hxg4 Qf2+ 20. Kh2 Qh4+ 21. Kg1) 17. Rxe5)) 16. Rb1 Bg4?! { While this develops the bishop with tempo, the piece ultimately doesn't belong on this square, so the tempo will have to be returned to white later. } 17. Qc2 Qxc2 18. Bxc2 Rae8 19. Be3 b6 20. Bb3 Kh8 { Getting off of the killer diagonal. I saw a few variations where white was able to play Ne4 by taking advantage of the pin. } 21. Bg5 Ne4 { While this move is tactically working, it is not wise to trade pieces when you are left with an isolated pawn. } 22. Nxe4 dxe4 23. h3 Bf5 24. Be3 Be6 { Thinking this was my bad bishop, I was happy to trade it off for white's annoyingly active bishop. With my pawn structure as it is, I am already playing for the draw... } 25. Bxe6 Rxe6 26. b3 Rfe8 27. Red1 Kg8 28. Kf1 Kf7 29. Ke2 R6e7 30. Rbc1 Kf6 31. Rc4 Bb8 32. Rdc1 h6 33. Rc6+ Kf7 34. Rc8 { Though this activates white's rook, the resultant position is a simple draw because my rook, king, and bishop hold down all the base points and entrance squares. } 34... Rxc8 35. Rxc8 Bc7 36. Ra8 Be5 37. Rc8 Bc7 38. Ra8 Be5 39. Rc8 Bc7 *


