1. e4 e6 2. f4 d5 3. Nf3 dxe4 4. Ng5 f5 5. Qh5+ g6 6. Qh3 Nf6 7. Bc4 Qd6 8. Qb3 Ke7? (8... Nc6! { I was analyzing these lines, but I couldn't quite make sure I was dealing with all the threats. So seeing that the dark squared bishop could not get on the a3-f8 diagonal, I went in for the game's crazy Ke7 move. } 9. Nxe6 (9. Bxe6 Nd4 10. Qc3 Bxe6 11. Nxe6 Nxe6 12. Qxf6 Bg7!) 9... Bxe6 10. Bxe6 Nd4 11. Bf7+ Ke7 12. Qc3 Kxf7) 9. Nc3 a6 (9... h6 10. Nb5 Qb6 { I was sure this was losing. Surprisingly, it still holds an advantage for black. }) 10. d3 b5! { Even though black's development is awful, this move traps the bishop, getting the rook into the game after an inevitable piece sacrifice on b5. } 11. Nxb5 (11. Bxb5 axb5 12. Nxb5 Qb6 { The line I had prepared against the scarier knight landing on b5. }) 11... axb5 12. Bxb5 h6 (12... exd3 13. Bd2 Bg7 14. Bb4 c5 { It's quite scary, but it should also be holdable. I saw no reason to open up the e and d files for white's rooks, so I went with the calmer exchanges. }) 13. dxe4 hxg5 14. e5 Qd5 15. exf6+ Kf7 (15... Kxf6!? { The move I wanted to play. } 16. Qc3+ Kf7 17. Qxh8 Qxb5 { I was sure there was compensation here for the exchange, but then I visualized a bishop getting to c3, and all of the attacking pieces converging on the weak f6 square... I chickened out. }) 16. fxg5? (16. Qxd5 exd5 17. fxg5 { I'm up a piece, but this endgame still requires some work. It is clear I am not getting mated though, and I have a solid blockade on the light squares. So it should be a matter of technique. }) 16... Qxg2 17. Rf1 Rxh2 { Now who is attacking whom? } 18. Be3 Qxc2 (18... Bc5!? 19. O-O-O Bxe3+ 20. Qxe3 Qxc2# { I missed the obvious mate in 1 at the end of this line... }) 19. Rc1 Qxb3 20. Rxc7+ Kg8 (20... Bd7 21. Rxd7+ (21. axb3 Ra1+ 22. Rc1 Rxc1+ 23. Bxc1 Bxb5 { It's a similar line to the game, but forcefully wins another piece on b5. }) 21... Nxd7 22. axb3) 21. axb3 Ra1+ 22. Bc1?? { Wanting to keep the active rook on the 7th file, white blunders. This blunder allows the spectacular finish though. } 22... Bb4+ 23. Kd1 Rd2+! 24. Ke1 Rc2+ 25. Rc3 (25. Kd1 Raxc1#) 25... Raxc1# *


