1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 { [%cal Ge1g1,Gg8f6,Gb8c6] } 4. d3 { [%cal Gd7d6] } (4. O-O Nxe4 (4... d6 5. c3 Be7 6. d4) 5. d4 Nd6 { [%cal Gd6b5] } 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8) 4... d6 (4... Bc5 5. c3 { [%cal Gd3d4] }) 5. O-O Be7 6. c3 O-O { [%cal Gd3d4,Gf6e4] } 7. Re1 { [%cal Gd3d4] } 7... a6 8. Ba4 b5 9. Bc2 Nb8!? { Retreats from in front of the c pawn so that an eventual c5 move can be supported. Unblocks the long diagonal for the bishop as well. } 10. h3 { Supporting the center so that d4 can be achieved and the pawn duo can be maintained. } { [%cal Gd3d4,Gc7c5] } 10... Bb7 11. d4 Nbd7 12. a4 Re8 13. Nbd2 { By transposition we have reached one of the mainlines of the Ruy Lopez. } { [%csl Gf5,Gh5][%cal Gd2f1,Gf1g3,Gb1d2] } 13... Bf8 14. Bd3! { "Forces" c6, blocking in the bishop. This allows the d2 knight to reposition to its preferred square (g3) without dropping e4. } 14... c6 15. Nf1 Qc7 16. Ng3 { [%cal Gg3f5,Gg3h5] } 16... g6 17. h4!? { My bishop on c1 doesn't truly have a better square for it. So I figured an h4-h5 attack would only benefit white (due to his weakening g6 move). } (17. Bg5!? h6 18. Be3 Bg7 19. Qd2 Kh7 20. dxe5 dxe5 21. c4! { After several forcing moves, white breaks with c4! Ruining black's pawn structure means white has a long term advantage due to the queenside targets. } { [%cal Gb5b4] }) 17... Bg7 (17... d5 { The move I was considering the most. Admittedly, it's hard to say who benefits more from keeping all the tension. I was planning } 18. exd5 cxd5 19. Nxe5 Nxe5 20. dxe5 Rxe5 21. Rxe5 Qxe5 { but I couldn't evaluate the position clearly. }) 18. h5 Nf8 (18... Nxh5 19. Nxh5 gxh5 20. Nh4 $16) 19. hxg6?! (19. Ng5 Rad8 20. h6 Bh8 (20... Bxh6 21. Nxf7 Bxc1 22. Nxd8 Bxb2 23. Qb3+ Kg7 24. Qxb2 Rxd8) 21. Be3 Ne6 22. axb5 axb5 23. dxe5 dxe5 24. Nxe6 Rxe6 25. Qe2 { A computer line that showcases why keeping the tension/installing the thorn pawn can actually be beneficial to white. }) 19... hxg6 20. dxe5 dxe5 { Releasing the tension in the center is almost always a bad idea, but I saw that keeping black's dark-squared bishop bad would be useful in the ensuing middlegame. } 21. Qb3?! (21. Ng5 { Stopping Ne6 on my terms must be correct if I am satisfied with trading the knights. } 21... N8h7 22. Qb3) 21... Ne6 22. Ng5 Nxg5?! { Returning the favor and transposing to the more benign line seen above. } (22... Nf4! { Taking the knight would activate the bishop and rook of my opponent (all while giving up the bishop pair) }) 23. Bxg5 Rad8 24. Rad1 Rd7 25. Bb1 { Out of ideas on how to improve the position, I transferred the bishop off the open file to the diagonal opposite the king. Completely missing the pawn break that benefits white the most. } { [%cal Gb1a2,Ga2f7] } (25. c4! Red8 26. axb5 cxb5 27. cxb5 axb5) 25... Red8 26. Ba2 Rxd1 27. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 28. Qxd1 { [%cal Gb7c8] } 28... Bc8 29. axb5 axb5 30. Qd3 { My more active bishops means white cannot be worse, but there's no further weaknesses to probe for... } 30... Nh7! 31. Be3 Nf8! { A brilliant maneuver to trade bishops and get a strong knight to e6. } 32. Nf1 Be6 33. Bxe6 Nxe6 34. g3 Bf8 35. Nh2 { [%csl Gg4] } 35... Qd6 { It's harder for black to make progress with the queens still on the board. I foolishly thought that there was no more progress black could make without the queens on, but fall right into an ensuing positional squeeze. } 36. Qxd6 Bxd6 37. Ng4 { Stopping f5 due to Nh6+ } 37... Kf8 38. Kf1 Ke7 39. Ke2? { I was watching for the f5 break for the past few moves, but didn't adequately prepare for it (thinking f3 and Ke2 were interchangeable). While the engine considers them equal, my task now becomes hapless as I struggle to hold a draw. } (39. f3! f5 40. Nf2 { This pawn transformation would be vastly superior to the one that happens in the game. }) 39... f5 40. exf5 (40. Nh2!? fxe4 41. Ng4 { I was considering this pawn sacrifice just as a way to activate my knight, but ultimately decided that black would keep the pawn and gain a positional advantage. I opted for a line that kept material balanced. }) 40... gxf5 41. Nh2 (41. Nh6 Kf6 42. g4!? f4 43. Nf5 { I certainly missed this idea in the game. }) 41... c5 { [%csl Ge3] } 42. b3 { White struggles to keep pawns on light squares to avoid any queenside probing with the bishop, but these pawn moves work to block in white's knight from becoming active ever again. } 42... e4! { Obvious, but incredibly strong. White's knight is now a spectator. } { [%cal Gd6e5,Gh2f3,Gh2g4] } 43. Nf1 Be5 44. Kd2 Kd6 45. Kc2 Nc7! { The knight repositions to d5 where it dominates the board. This simply cannot be allowed. } 46. c4 b4 47. Nd2 Ne6 48. Nf1 (48. g4!! { The only drawing move. White disrupts the black pawns and gets the knight immediately into the game. I missed this completely, thinking that f4 would trap my bishop. } 48... fxg4 (48... f4 49. Nxe4+ Kc6 50. Bd2) 49. Nxe4+) 48... Nd4+ { [%csl Gb3] } 49. Kb2! { Taking the knight ends up in a hopelessly lost endgame due to the passed d pawn. Amazingly there are no back-breaking discovered checks after Kb2. } 49... Nf3+ 50. Kc2 Bd4 { Black has maneuvered every piece into its optimal square, but is there a breakthrough? } 51. Kc1 Ke6 52. Kc2 Kf6 { Black's plan of infiltrating with the king on the light-squares seems unstoppable... } 53. Kc1 Kg6 54. Kc2 Kh5 55. Kd1 Kg4 56. Nh2+!! { This is a brilliant move not because it wins (or draws) the game, but because it means that white will have some serious threats for the first time in 30 moves. } 56... Nxh2 (56... Kh3!? 57. Nxf3 Bxe3 58. Nh4 Bxf2 59. Nxf5 Bxg3 { The line I couldn't fully evaluate. I hoped this was enough for a draw, but blockading the e pawn will prove difficult. }) 57. Bxd4 cxd4 58. c5 { c5 reveals the point of white's knight sacrifice. White's c pawn cannot be stopped. } 58... Kf3 59. Ke1 (59. c6?? Kxf2 60. c7 e3 61. c8=Q e2+ { The win for black is too easy. }) 59... Ng4 60. c6 Nxf2?? { While it's true that black cannot stop white's pawn, black has enough resources to mate white with just the pawns, king, and knight. } (60... d3!! 61. c7 e3!! 62. fxe3 Kxe3 63. c8=Q d2+ 64. Kd1 Nf2+ 65. Kc2 d1=Q+ 66. Kb2 Nd3+ 67. Ka2 Qd2+ 68. Qc2 Qxc2+ 69. Ka1 Qb2#) 61. c7 { [%cal Gf2d3] } 61... Nd3+ 62. Kd2 e3+?? { Visually, not a terrible move, but now black has officially missed the key idea of how to queen the e pawn with check. } 63. Kxd3 e2 64. c8=Q e1=Q { [%cal Ge1c3] } 65. Qxf5+ Kxg3 66. Qg5+ Kf3 67. Qf5+ Kg3 68. Qg5+ Kf3 69. Qf5+ { A draw is agreed upon due to the unavoidable perpetual. } *


