1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bc4 Bg7 5. Bb3 O-O 6. Nf3 Bg4!? 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Nc6 9. Be3 { [%cal Ge7e5] } 9... Nd7?! (9... e5 { The most principled try - taking a claim in the center and neither dxe5 nor d5 are exactly what white wants. } 10. dxe5 dxe5 (10... Nxe5!? { to keep the diagonal open })) 10. O-O-O a5 11. a4 { With both sides castled opposite to each other, this move slows the attack on white's king the most. } 11... e5 12. dxe5 Ndxe5 13. Qe2 { Retreats, but prepares f4, g4, and h4. } 13... Nd7! { Gets out of any f4 moves with tempo, prepares Nc5 to win the amazing light-squared bishop, and directly opens up the dark-squared bishop's diagonal. } 14. h4 h5?? { This move just encourages white's attack to hit faster with g4-h5. } (14... Bxc3?! 15. bxc3 { I didn't think there was compensation for giving up the beastly bishop. }) (14... Nc5?? { Would be a great move except for the pin on the d-file. } 15. Bxc5) 15. g4 hxg4 16. Qxg4 Nde5 (16... Nf6?? 17. Qxg6) 17. Qg2 Qd7 { [%cal Gf2f4,Ge5g4] } 18. Rdg1 { All of white's pieces are aimed directly at black's king, and there is no way to stop f4-f5 (followed by Qxh6) or the slower h5. } 18... d5! { Muddies the waters the most. } 19. Bxd5 Nb4 20. Bb3 Ra6 21. f4 { Forces black to sacrifice the knight. White is certainly winning. } 21... Ned3+ 22. cxd3 (22. Kb1!?) 22... Bxc3 23. bxc3 Qxd3 24. Qd2 Qxe4 { Giving up a second piece. But is there counterplay? } 25. cxb4 Rd6 26. Bc2 Qc4 (26... Qxh1 27. Rxh1 Rxd2 28. Bxd2 $18) 27. Qf2 { [%cal Gf4f5] } 27... Qa2 28. Bxg6 (28. Bd4! Rfd8 29. Bb2 { And white's king could not be safer. White will easily win this. }) 28... Qa3+ (28... Qxf2 29. Bc2+ Qxg1+ 30. Rxg1+ Kh8 31. Bc5 $18) 29. Kb1 Qxb4+ (29... fxg6 30. Qa2+ Qxa2+ 31. Kxa2 $18 { The queens are traded and white remains a piece ahead. }) 30. Qb2 Rxg6 31. Qxb4 axb4 { White is ahead, but these queenside pawns can get rolling quite quickly. } 32. h5! { Forcing Rxg1 and ensuring white has a passed h pawn. } 32... Rxg1+ 33. Rxg1+ Kh7 34. Bd4 Rd8 35. Bf6 Rd7 (35... Rd6 36. Rg7+ Kh6 37. Rxf7 { The other variation gets white's rook on the 7th. }) 36. Kc2 c5 37. Rd1!? { I wanted to simplify into a simple winning endgame, but it is so difficult to see all the variations correctly... } 37... b3+! (37... Rc7) 38. Kc1 Rxd1+ 39. Kxd1 Kh6 40. Kd2 Kxh5 41. Kc3 Kg4 42. Be5 f6! { White has the wrong bishop to promote the a pawn. Which means that black has a draw if he can get his king to a8. } 43. Bxf6 Kxf4 44. Kxb3 Kf5 45. Kc4!! { The bishop is not necessary to win here. And every tempo counts in the race to get the kings to a8. } 45... Ke6 (45... Kxf6?? 46. Kxc5 Ke7 47. Kb6 Kd7 48. Kxb7) (45... b6!? 46. Bc3 Ke6 47. Kb5 Kd7 48. Kxb6 Kc8 49. Ka7 Kc7 50. a5 Kc6 51. a6 Kc7 52. Be5+ Kc8 53. Kb6) 46. Kxc5 Kd7 47. Kb6 Kc8 48. Be5! { And white is just there in time to stop black's king from getting to the corner. White will push through and queen the a pawn. } *


