1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. Nf3 (4. g4 { I usually play with g4 here. Having just played the Pirc vs this person in a different move order, I wasn't paying attention to the fact that Nd7 was played before e5. }) 4... e5 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6 8. a4 { Stops any expansion ideas with b5, but does allow for the center to be liquidated as in the game. } 8... exd4 9. Nxd4 Ne5 10. Be2!? { Stops any annoying Bg4 moves, and prepares a potential f4-e5 expansion. } (10. Bb3 c5! 11. Nf5 Bxf5 12. exf5 c4 { The move order I was most worried about if I kept the bishop on the long diagonal. }) 10... d5 11. f4! Nc4 12. e5 Bc5!! { I had initially thought that e5 was simply winning material, but the fantastic Bc5 move holds it all together. } 13. Kh1 { Calm and collected, the king can sidestep the pin and the threats must now be addressed. } (13. exf6?? Qxf6 { And the knight on d4 will be lost. }) 13... Ne8?! { Surely one of the other knight jumps would have been stronger? I take this opportunity to induce structural damage to black's queenside majority, at the price of the bishop pair. Now I hope to push my kingside majority and make a queen first. } 14. Bxc4! dxc4 15. Be3 Bb6 16. Nf3?! { Retreating the centrally placed knight cannot be best. But it seemed important to stabilize my pieces and get out of any pins before looking to improve other pieces. } (16. Ne4!? Qd5 { I was unsure what to do if we had gotten to this position. My knight on e4 looks good, but doesn't really have any good squares to jump to. }) 16... Nc7 17. Bxb6 (17. Qe2! Bxe3 18. Qxe3 Bf5 19. Nd4 { Focusing on pushing the majority immediately would have been better than the game. }) 17... Qxd1 18. Rexd1 { Which way to recapture? My e rook was supporting e6, but my knight and a rook are preventing b5. } 18... axb6 19. h3 { Preparing g4 and rolling with my kingside majority. } (19. Rd4?! Bf5 { My knight is the piece that wants to occupy d4 in this line. }) 19... f6!! { Breaks down the head of my pawn chain without allowing any counterplay. } 20. exf6 (20. Kg1 fxe5 21. fxe5?? Bxh3 { White cannot create a passed pawn without losing the h3 pawn. }) 20... Rxf6 21. Rd8+ Rf8 22. Rxf8+ (22. Rad1!? Bf5 23. Rxa8 Rxa8 24. Nd4 { I did not feel like white had any advantage in this line, but perhaps it is more solid than in the game. }) 22... Kxf8 23. g4 { Now Ne5 becomes a threat to win the c4 pawn. } 23... b5! { I had completely missed the fact that after the a1 rook is no longer supported, white can no longer capture on b5. } 24. Kg2 b6 25. Ne5 Nd5! (25... Bb7 26. Nd7+ Ke7 27. Nxb6 Ra6 28. a5 { I saw that the obvious ways to defend c6 would fail. }) 26. Kg3?! { Defends f4 and avoids any pins along the long diagonal. But it is too slow due to a fantastic series of exchanges by black. } (26. Nxd5!? cxd5 27. b3 bxa4 28. bxa4 b5 { Black has an incredibly mobile majority. I did not want to allow these pawn advances in our race to queen the pawns. }) 26... Nxc3 27. bxc3 bxa4! 28. Nxc4 b5 { Black has given up hope of maintaining the extra pawn in exchange for a mobile queenside majority. } 29. Ne5 c5 30. Nd3! c4 { Now that the black pawns have been slowed down, I reposition my knight to d4 where it can defend the base pawn on c2 and attack the weak b5 pawn. In retrospect, going immediately to b4 would have been better as it allows me to activate my king and push the kingside majority immediately. } 31. Ne5 (31. Nb4!? Kf7 32. f5 Kf6 33. Kf4) 31... Ke7 32. Nc6+ Kd6 33. Nd4 Bd7 34. f5 a3 35. Ra2 { It is important to stop the pawn before it can land on a light square (and also to avoid black from being able to play Ra3 themselves). } 35... Kd5 { I can see that b4 is coming, but I'm helpless to stop it. } 36. Kf4 (36. Nf3! Ke4 37. Nd2+!! Ke3 38. Nb1 { A very interesting maneuver that doesn't immediately lose the game. }) 36... b4 { Black's majority pushes through first. I didn't feel it was worthwhile fighting on with Ne2 due to b3!, but Ke3 is an interesting alternative to try and maintain the knight's beastly post. However, it too fails (to Re8+). } *


