1. e4 { [%cal Gd7d5] } 1... e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. Nf3?! { Without lending support to the center with f4, it's possible black can tear it down easily, as in this game. } 5... c5 6. Bb5 Nc6 7. O-O cxd4 8. Nxd4 Ncxe5?! (8... Ndxe5!? 9. f4 a6! (9... Nd7!? 10. f5 e5 11. Nf3 Bc5+ 12. Kh1 a6 13. Ba4) 10. Ba4 Nd7! 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bxc6?? Qb6+) 9. Re1 Bd6 10. Bf4 (10. f4!? Nc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bxc6?? { The other line I was worried about turns out to be a blunder! } 12... Qb6+) 10... Qf6 11. Bg3? { Now I'm just up a pawn as I have time to castle out of danger } (11. Bxd7+ Bxd7 12. Nxd5!! exd5 13. Bxe5 Bxe5 14. Nf3 { All these threats are based on the fact that my king is stuck in the center with no e pawn to shelter me }) 11... O-O 12. f4 Ng6 13. Qd2 a6 (13... Bxf4 14. Bxf4 (14. Rf1?? Bxd2 15. Rxf6 Nxf6) 14... Qxf4 { I need to work on my calculation abilities. Some lines that I'm worried about turn out to be extremely good for me. }) (13... Qxd4+ 14. Qxd4 Bc5) 14. Ba4 Nc5 15. Rf1 { Now the pawn is directly defended, and f5 cannot be met with Bxg3, Bxe1, I need to recognize that f5 can be a real threat. } { [%cal Gb7b5] } 15... Nxa4 (15... b5 16. Bb3 b4 17. Nce2 Ne4) 16. Nxa4 { [%cal Gf6d8] } 16... b5 17. Nb6 Rb8 18. Nxc8 Rbxc8 19. f5 { I visualized this position from move 15, but completely missed that Bxg3 wasn't working anymore. Even looking at this position with fresh eyes, I jumped at Bxg3, missing the fact that I'm losing a piece. } 19... Bxg3?? (19... Bc5! { This resource can be used to get out of losing a piece for 3 pawns. } 20. c3 exf5) 20. fxg6? Bxh2+ 21. Kxh2 Qxg6 22. c3 { Now that the dust has settled, black has 3 pawns for a piece. But if the pawns cannot push, the piece has a huge advantage. } 22... Rc4 23. b3?! { Why weaken the c pawn unnecessarily? } 23... Rc5 24. Rae1 Rfc8 25. Rf3 { White needs to ensure the central pawns are contained. In the meantime, he can maximize pressure on my king by tripling up on the f file (or g file). If black has to defend passively, then there's no way to prove the pawns are worth anything. } 25... a5!? { Trying to get a little counterplay with b4 - sacrificing a pawn just to open the c file and get some activity. If the c pawn budges, then black will have 2 central connected passed pawns. If only they could advance... } 26. Ref1 Qh5+ 27. Rh3?! { White is losing track of his goal. } { [%cal Gf1f7] } 27... Qe5+ 28. Kg1 b4 29. cxb4 axb4 30. Rhf3 (30. Qxb4 Rc1 31. Rf3 Rxf1+ { The line white tried to avoid with the "greedy" Qxb4 } { [%csl Ge3,Gh6] }) 30... Qh5 31. Rh3 (31. Rxf7!? { The computer suggestion makes sense because now white is taking on b5 at the end of the line and getting 2 connected passed pawns himself. } 31... Qxf7 32. Rxf7 Kxf7 33. Qxb4) 31... Qg6 { Setting up one more trick. } 32. Rff3?? (32. Qxb4 Rc1 33. Rf3 { In this line I still didn't think I had anything. The engine confirms it, but at least it's less losing than previous lines. }) 32... Rc2! 33. Nxc2 Rxc2 { The pressure on g2 means that white will have to give back material in order to avoid mate. } 34. Qxc2? (34. Rc3! Rxc3 35. Rxc3 bxc3 36. Qxc3 h5 { A very interesting alternative by white. At least here, it's a queen endgame with 2 connected passers on the queenside. }) 34... Qxc2 35. Rf2 Qc1+ 36. Rf1 Qc5+ 37. Kh1 f6 { Black wins by maintaining a centralized queen, pushing the central pawns, and stopping white from doubling up on any weaknesses. } 38. Rd3 e5 39. Rdd1 Kf7 40. Rc1 Qe3 41. Rc2 (41. Rc7+ Ke6! 42. Rc6+ (42. Rxg7?? Qh6+) 42... Kd7 43. Rfc1 e4 { The line I was considering here. Black is pushing through unhindered. }) 41... e4 { Stops the rook from getting any activity on c4. White has nothing and quickly resigned out of frustration. } 42. Rcf2 Ke6 *


