1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 h6 7. Nf3 Nd7 8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Ngf6 11. Bd2 e6 12. O-O-O { All mainline caro kann stuff. } 12... Qc7 13. Kb1 O-O-O 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Nf6 16. Qe2 { The typical caro kann maneuver of trading off one pair of knights so as to get in g4 potentially has been achieved. } 16... Bd6 (16... c5!? { I was curious how to move forward here actually. It seems wrong to open the position up, but it destroys any space advantage white had. } 17. dxc5 Bxc5 18. Rh4!?) 17. c4 Kb8 18. Bc3 Rhe8 (18... c5 { Again an interesting try. Here though I have enough support for Ne5. } 19. Ne5 $14) 19. Ne5 { Forcing me to play Ne5. Otherwise black gets in e5, and all hopes for an advantage are gone. } 19... Re7 (19... Bxe5? 20. dxe5 Nd7 21. Rd6 $16) 20. g4 Nd7 21. f4! { White takes over the kingside with a huge space advantage. The only hope for black is that f6 works. } 21... f6 (21... Bxe5 22. dxe5 $16 { [%csl Gd6] }) 22. Ng6 Rf7 23. Qxe6 (23. f5! exf5 24. c5! Bg3 (24... Bf8 { [%cal Gc3d2,Gd2f4] } 25. Qe6) (24... Bf4 25. Qc4 Nf8 26. Nxf4 Qxf4 27. Qxf7 fxg4) 25. Qc4! Nf8 26. Ba5!! { [%cal Gc7a5,Gc4f7] } 26... Qxa5 27. Qxf7 Nxg6 28. hxg6 fxg4 29. Qxg7) 23... Nf8!! { Forced. But allows black to gain the necessary tempo to win the pawn back. } 24. Nxf8 Bxf8 (24... Rfxf8 25. f5?? Rfe8) 25. Rhf1 Re7 26. Qf5 Rde8 27. Rfe1 Re2!? { Black persists in getting activity. } 28. d5 c5 29. Rxe2 (29. Be5! { Disconnect in the rooks! }) 29... Rxe2 30. g5 Bd6 (30... hxg5 31. fxg5 fxg5?? { [%csl Gf8] }) 31. gxf6 gxf6 32. Qxf6 Bxf4?? 33. Qf8+ { [%csl Gf4] } 33... Qc8 34. Qxf4+ Ka8 35. d6 *


