1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5 4. c3 Nge7 5. O-O a6 6. Ba4 O-O 7. d4 exd4 8. cxd4 Bb6 9. d5 Nb8 (9... Na5?! { I was calculating this variation and couldn't see how to take advantage of black's misplaced knights before black played Nb8. } 10. b4 Nc4 11. Qd3 Nd6 12. e5 Ndf5 13. d6! { The stunner that I didn't (yet) see. }) 10. Nc3?! (10. d6!! { Keep the a3-g8 diagonal open! While this destroys your own strong center, it keeps the queenside pieces bottled up for a long time. } 10... cxd6 11. Nc3 Nbc6 12. Bf4 { The pawn will be won back, and the pieces remain poorly placed. }) 10... d6 11. h3 Nd7 12. Bc2 { Played because of who I was facing. He loves to play f5 even when it's not great. } (12. Re1 Ne5 { I was not sure how to continue here, even though I was fairly certain he'd play f5 instead of Ne5. }) 12... f5 { Played anyway! } 13. Ng5 { Threatening to hop into e6. } 13... Nf6 (13... Ne5!? 14. Qh5 h6 { Sadly there is no follow-up here for white. }) 14. exf5 Nxf5 15. Ne6!? (15. Re1!? { Gives more support to e6, but I was again unsure how to continue after Nd4! } 15... Nd4 16. Be3!? Nxc2 17. Qxc2 Bxe3 18. Rxe3 { The line where white retains his advantage. }) 15... Bxe6 16. dxe6 { Is the e pawn a strength or a weakness? I was thinking I could consolidate after a Nd5, Nxd5, Qxd5 maneuver here, but I missed the ensuing move. } 16... Ng3! { The computer hates this move, but proving it required more than 30 minutes of calculation from both sides. } (16... Nd4!? 17. Bg5 Nxe6 18. Bb3 { The correct response to Nd4 - the move I was expecting black to play. }) 17. Re1 Ng4! { Black piles on pressure to f7 with a stunning move. } (17... Bxf2+?? 18. Kxf2 Nfe4+ (18... Ng4+ 19. Kxg3) 19. Kg1 { There is no follow-up. }) 18. Qxg4 { Forced. I saw that I could give up f7 and eventually win back a piece with the Bf4 double attack. } 18... Bxf2+ (18... Rxf2 19. Be3 $18) 19. Kh2 Bxe1 20. Bf4! Nf1+!? 21. Kg1 Qh4 { With another great attacking move, black gets all of his pieces into the attack. Thankfully, I have just enough pieces around in order to win back and defend everything. } 22. Qxh4 Bxh4 23. Rxf1 Rae8 24. Bb3 Kh8 { Now the game has slowed down and it becomes a rook vs 2 piece endgame. I was desperately trying to reach an endgame where it was two bishops vs the rook, but my opponent was solid and never traded unless it was going to be an even trade. } 25. Ne4 Rf5 26. g3 Be7 27. Rd1 Ref8 28. Rd5? g5 (28... Rxd5 29. Bxd5 c6 30. Bxd6 (30. Bb3 d5 { This structural change must be avoided. }) 30... cxd5 31. Bxe7 Re8! { The move I missed in my calculations. Now not only is it not even, but black is the one winning! }) 29. Rxf5 Rxf5 30. Bd2 { Keeps the bishop honed in on g5, also allows for use of the long diagonal in a lot of situations. } 30... d5?? { The right idea, but the wrong execution. Black miscalculated somewhere in the following lines, but white regains the pawn and his dangerous e pawn proves victorious. } (30... c6!? 31. Bc3+ Kg8 { I was unsure how to stop the threat of d5 here. } 32. Nxd6! Bxd6?? 33. e7+) 31. g4! Rf3 32. Bxd5! (32. Nxg5?? { My initial idea fails to } 32... Bc5+ { And the undefended d2 bishop will be won next. Seeing this in the game, I took a closer look at Bxd5 and saw the win. }) 32... Rd3 33. Bc4 Rxh3 34. Bxg5!! { I had been avoiding a knight and bishop vs rook endgame for the entire endgame, but now I see a direct path to pushing the passed pawn through! Taking with the knight allows both a Bc5+ and a Rg3+ that must be avoided. } (34. Kg2?! Rh4 { My initial idea was much weaker than the game. }) 34... Bxg5 35. Nxg5 Rg3+ (35... Re3 36. Kf2 { My knight and bishop cover every square on the e file. Black must give up the rook for the pawn. } { [%csl Ge4,Ge2,Ge1,Ge6] } 36... Re5 37. Nf7+) 36. Kf2 Rxg4 37. e7!! { White pushes through with both pieces hanging. Black resigned rather than playing Rxg5. } *


